# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hono-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:hono-framework/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:hono-framework/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:hono-framework/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:hono-framework/page] Hono - ***means flame🔥 in Japanese*** - is a small, simple, and ultrafast web framework built on Web Standards.
[src:hono-framework/page] It works on any JavaScript runtime: Cloudflare Workers, Fastly Compute, Deno, Bun, Vercel, Netlify, AWS Lambda, Lambda@Edge, and Node.js.
[src:hono-framework/page] Hono is a simple web application framework similar to Express, without a frontend.
[src:hono-framework/page] But it runs on CDN Edges and allows you to construct larger applications when combined with middleware.
[src:hono-framework/page] A demonstration to create an application for Cloudflare Workers with Hono.
[src:hono-framework/page] Thanks to the use of the **Web Standards**, Hono works on a lot of platforms.
[src:hono-framework/page] And by using a Node.js adapter, Hono works on Node.js.
[src:hono-framework/page] See more information about Web Standards.
[src:hono-framework/page] Hono provides a delightful "**Developer Experience**".
[src:hono-framework/page] Easy access to Request/Response thanks to the `Context` object.
[src:hono-framework/page] Moreover, Hono is written in TypeScript.
[src:hono-framework/page] For example, the path parameters will be literal types.
[src:hono-framework/page] (A screenshot showing Hono having proper literal typing when URL parameters.
[src:hono-framework/page] And, the Validator and Hono Client `hc` enable the RPC mode.
[src:hono-framework/page] In RPC mode, you can use your favorite validator such as Zod and easily share server-side API specs with the client and build type-safe applications.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:hono-framework/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:hono-framework/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:hono-framework/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:hono-framework/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
